<DocsLayout title="Introduction">

<h1>Introduction</h1>

<p class="lead">
Welcome to the <strong>Zero-Day Handbook</strong> — a free, open guide to
understanding how zero-day vulnerabilities are found, exploited, disclosed,
and fixed. It's written for people who are curious about security but don't
want to wade through a dense academic paper to get the basics right.
</p>

<p>
A single unpatched flaw has taken down hospital networks, exposed millions
of encryption keys, and given nation-states silent access to activists'
phones. Zero-days sit at the center of almost every major cybersecurity
story of the last two decades — this handbook exists to make that world
legible, one concept at a time.
</p>

<hr />

<h2>What You'll Find Here</h2>

<div class="topic-list">

  <a href={`${base}docs/zero-day`} class="topic">
    <span class="topic-num">01</span>
    <div>
      <h3>What is a Zero-Day?</h3>
      <p>Core definitions, terminology, and where the name actually comes from.</p>
    </div>
  </a>

  <a href={`${base}docs/lifecycle`} class="topic">
    <span class="topic-num">02</span>
    <div>
      <h3>Vulnerability Lifecycle</h3>
      <p>The five stages every vulnerability moves through, from discovery to patch.</p>
    </div>
  </a>

  <a href={`${base}docs/case-studies`} class="topic">
    <span class="topic-num">03</span>
    <div>
      <h3>Case Studies</h3>
      <p>Five real incidents — Stuxnet, WannaCry, Heartbleed, Log4Shell, and Pegasus.</p>
    </div>
  </a>

  <a href={`${base}docs/linux-security`} class="topic">
    <span class="topic-num">04</span>
    <div>
      <h3>Linux Security</h3>
      <p>Why Linux is a prime target, and how servers are actually hardened against it.</p>
    </div>
  </a>

  <a href={`${base}docs/references`} class="topic">
    <span class="topic-num">05</span>
    <div>
      <h3>References</h3>
      <p>Databases, standards, and further reading to go deeper on any topic here.</p>
    </div>
  </a>

</div>

<h2>Who This Is For</h2>

<p>
You don't need a security background to follow along. If you're a developer
curious about how the bugs you ship could be exploited, a student getting
into cybersecurity, or just someone who wants to understand what's actually
behind the next "zero-day" headline — this is written for you.
</p>

<hr />

<h2>About the Author</h2>

<div class="author-card">

  <div class="author-top">
    <div class="author-avatar">RM</div>
    <div>
      <h3>Rudra Kumar Mavi</h3>
      <p class="author-role">Computer Science Engineering student · AI/ML</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p class="author-bio">
    I'm a CSE student specializing in AI/ML, with a strong pull toward
    cybersecurity, DevSecOps, and OSINT tooling. I built this handbook to
    turn what I've learned researching zero-days into something clear
    enough for anyone to pick up. On the security side, I focus on
    source-code review — finding the gap between what a spec promises and
    what the implementation actually does — rather than pure black-box
    recon.
  </p>

